article.description: Glenn Robinson scored a season-high 37 points and Alan Henderson grabbed a career-high 21 rebounds playing out of position as the Atlanta Hawks edged the Seattle SuperSonics in overtime, 119-116.
article.headline: Hawks commit 27 TOs, but outrebound Sonics 55-32
article.linkText: Hawks beat Sonics despite season-high 27 turnovers
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Coach Lon Kruger had to temper his enthusiasm after the Atlanta Hawks ended a three-game losing streak.
Abdur-Rahim

Robinson

"Our carelessness with the ball,'' Kruger said, "is something we're not going to survive.'' Glenn Robinson scored a season-high 37 points and Shareef Abdur-Rahim added 31 as the Hawks beat the Seattle SuperSonics 119-116 in overtime Tuesday night despite committing a season-high 27 turnovers. Entering with the NBA's second-highest average in turnovers, the Hawks' miscues led to 30 points for the Sonics, who committed only seven. "Some games are like that,'' Jason Terry said. "It's very mystifying.'' Alan Henderson started in place of Theo Ratliff (flu) and pulled down a career-high 21 rebounds to help Atlanta overcome a season-high 32 points from Gary Payton. The Hawks led for almost the entire overtime after Abdur-Rahim missed a running jumper at the end of regulation, leaving the score tied 105-105. Terry's 3-pointer from the left side of the key gave Atlanta its biggest overtime lead, 114-107 with 2:52 remaining. Reserve guard Desmond Mason, who had 23 points for the Sonics, answered with a 15-footer, but they never drew any closer than one after Rashard Lewis' 3-pointer at the 37.9-second mark. For Seattle-area native Terry, the victory was especially important after the Hawks played so poorly down the stretch in an overtime loss Friday at Boston. The Celtics led throughout Saturday's rematch. "We were really disappointed,'' Terry said. "I think we learned from it.'' Atlanta outrebounded Seattle 55-32. "They didn't kind of hurt us on the boards,'' Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. "They killed us. They dominated us. Whether or not it was our worst game or not, I don't know, but it was bad enough.'' Brent Barry, whose 3-pointer with 4.7 seconds to go gave the Sonics a one-point win at San Antonio on Sunday night, missed a 3 from the right wing, and the ball went off the Hawks with six-tenths of a second remaining in OT. Lewis heaved a 3-point attempt that bounced high off the backboard at the buzzer. Though Barry fed him from the top of the key for a layup with 5.4 seconds left to force overtime, Lewis made a careless move after Abdur-Rahim's free throws put Atlanta on top 104-103. Lewis tried for a dunk on a nice pass from Barry, but the ball bounced hard off the rim and gave the Hawks possession. "We never had a rhythm or control of the game,'' said McMillan, whose team has lost three of four. "Even when we got the one-point lead a couple of times, we never really established ourselves.'' Robinson committed a game-high seven turnovers, but he was 12-for-20 from the floor and pulled down 12 rebounds. "The key is to try to push up on him and make him put the ball on the floor, but in my opinion he's probably the best mid-range player in the game right now,'' Barry said. "He's a throwback type of player and can get it going with one or two defenders on him.'' Robinson thought the biggest difference was Terry, who handed out a game-high 10 assists. "We had to move the ball,'' Robinson said. "If we have to play one-on-one with this team, we'll never win.''

Game notes
Henderson's previous high in rebounds was 15, which he reached three times. ... Seattle was only 2-for-11 on 3-point attempts. ... Terry missed six straight shots and hadn't scored in the second half until his 3 cut the Seattle lead to 87-86 midway through the fourth.
